Under Ohio Revised Code Section 5721.19(D), a former owner or junior lienholder generally has 90 days from the date the court enters its order confirming the sale to file a claim. The claim is filed by motion inside the same court case that ordered the foreclosure, not as a new lawsuit. Claims filed after the 90-day window are typically barred, and unclaimed funds are transferred to the county general fund.

To support a claim, you will generally need to show a recorded interest in the property at the time of sale, such as a deed, mortgage, or judgment lien, along with a certified copy of the relevant recorded instrument from the county recorder. If the former owner has passed away, the estate typically needs to be opened in probate court, though some courts will accept an affidavit of heirship in limited circumstances.

Ohio law does not set a statutory cap on recovery fees for this type of claim. Any fee agreement with a recovery professional should clearly state the percentage or other compensation method before you sign anything.

Given that claims must be filed within an active court case and deadlines are firm, we recommend speaking with an Ohio-licensed attorney if you believe you have a valid interest. We are happy to review the county records with you and explain what documentation is typically required. This letter is informational only and is not legal advice.

